🤯Onion & Garlic:Good as Medicine but Bad Food?🧅
🔹 Ayurveda's truth revealed

Garlic and onion are not “bad” — but they’re not meant for daily food in a sattvic diet. They’re medicinal herbs in Ayurveda, best used with purpose, not habit.

 ✅ When to use them as medicine:

🧄 Garlic (Lahsun)
• Boosts immunity in cold & flu
• Reduces bloating and Vata gas
• Supports heart health & lowers BP
• Anti-parasitic & detoxifying
Use: 1 raw clove in ghee in the morning or in decoctions

🧅 Onion (Palandu)
• Cools the body in heatstroke
• Relieves dry cough & sore throat
• Helps with skin rashes & insect bites
• Aphrodisiac in fatigue cases
Use: Raw juice, or warm onion poultice for relief

📿 But when taken daily as food, they’re tamasic and rajasic —
 clouding the mind, imbalancing doshas,causing anger ,anxiety,restlessness 
disturbing digestion & meditation.

✨ Choose Sattva over habit. Let food be truly healing.

👁️ Suffering from Eye Floaters or Weak Vision? Try This Ancient Ayurvedic Remedy! 🌿
If you notice black dots, threads, or flashes in your field of vision, you might be experiencing eye floaters. 

While common, they can be frustrating — and Ayurveda has a time-tested solution. 💧

✨ Remedy: Triphala Eye Wash
🟢 Soak 1 tsp of Triphala powder in a glass of water overnight.
🟢 In the morning, strain it using a clean muslin cloth or cotton.
🟢 Use the clear water to gently wash your eyes.
Do this daily for naturally cleansing the eyes, reducing fatigue, and supporting overall vision health.

Bonus Tip: Apply a drop of cow’s ghee in your navel at night for added eye nourishment! 🧈

For Triphala eye wash, classical Ayurvedic texts (like Ashtanga Hridaya and Sharangadhara Samhita) mention that Triphala Kashaya (decoction) prepared in equal parts (1:1:1) of Haritaki, Bibhitaki, and Amalaki is traditionally used for Netra Prakshalana (eye washing).

⚠️ Disclaimer:
This is a traditional Ayurvedic remedy and may not suit everyone. Please consult an Ayurvedic practitioner or eye specialist before trying any new treatment, especially if you have existing eye conditions.

👇 Follow for more ancient remedies that still work wonders today!

Ayurveda Superfoods - Wheat grass Juice 💥👇

💥Hindi Name- gehun, kanak, Sanskrit name- godhuma) is called as a wheat grass, belonging to family: Gramineae, which posses high chlorophyll content and essential vitamins, minerals, vital enzymes, amino acids, dietary fibers.

💥Wheatgrass is used in Ayurveda to treat high acid levels, inflammation in the colon, poor kidney function, and wounds.
💥 Ayurveda is a natural system of medicine that originated in India over 3,000 years ago, and its practitioners say that lifestyle changes and natural therapies can help balance your body, mind, spirit, and environment. 
💥Wheatgrass is also used in folk medicine to treat colds, coughs, fevers, gout, infections, joint pain, chronic skin disorders, constipation, and swelling of the throat and mouth.
💥About 70% of each sprout is made up of chlorophyll, which gives wheatgrass its bright green color. Chlorophyll is the green pigment that plants use to make food during photosynthesis. 
💥The structure of chlorophyll is similar to that of hemoglobin, the protein in your blood that carries oxygen to your tissues. So, it's sometimes also called “green blood.”

“Struggling to sleep on hot summer nights? Try this Ayurvedic bedtime ritual!”
🌸 Gulkand Milk: An Ayurvedic Summer Elixir

Gulkand, made from rose petals and sugar, possesses sweet and cooling properties. When combined with milk, it becomes an unctuous and nourishing drink. 

While Gulkand itself isn't mentioned in ancient texts, its components and their properties are well-regarded in Ayurveda.
 Combining Gulkand with milk creates a drink that embodies the qualities recommended for summer consumption, offering a natural way to stay cool and balanced during the hottest months.

💥This combination aligns with the Ayurvedic recommendations for summer, as it helps:

Cool the body and reduce heat-induced discomfort.
Balance Pitta dosha, which can become aggravated during the hot season.
Promote better sleep by calming the mind and body.

💥How to Use:
Take 1-2 teaspoons of Gulkand  in a glass of lukewarm or cold milk(cold to room temperature),30 minutes before bedtime. This natural coolant soothes the digestive system, calms the nerves, and may promote restful sleep.

Why it works:
According to Ayurveda, Gulkand pacifies aggravated Pitta dosha, which often disturbs sleep during hot months. Combined with milk, it nourishes, hydrates, and cools the body from within.

Disclaimer: This remedy is generally safe, but if you’re pregnant, diabetic, or on medication, consult your Ayurvedic doctor or healthcare provider before use.

Black Rice – The Ancient Supergrain You Need to Try!

Once reserved for royalty, 90% of India’s black rice is grown in #manipur ,Northeast India,it’s packed with both Ancient wisdom and modern nutrition.

💥From an Ayurvedic lens, it balances Vata & Pitta,cooling & Snigdh in nature builds Ojas, and supports blood health—but yes, it’s slightly heavy & slow to digest so prep is key!

💥Best way to consume Black rice:
Soak for 4–5 hours, then cook like regular rice (1 part rice : 5 parts water). Once soft, drain excess water. 

Pair with digestive spices to ease digestion.
💥To make Black Stir Rice:
Do a tempering in ghee with:
Jeera, star anise, cardamom, bay leaf, green chilli, ginger, cinnamon, sesame seeds,curry leaves then add the cooked rice and stir-fry for 3–4 minutes.

💥Other ways to enjoy:
Serve boiled black rice with a spice-rich gravy—this enhances taste and makes it easier to digest.

Modern science confirms its benefits:
Rich in antioxidants,fiber
8g protein, 3g fat, 75g carbs
Supports heart, brain & blood sugar health
High in fiber, iron & amino acids

A detox-friendly, nourishing grain rooted in tradition and backed by science.

Disclaimer: This content is for informational purposes only and not a substitute for medical advice. Please consult your health practitioner for personalized guidance.

"Hadjod" literally translates to “bone setter” or “that which protects the bone from destruction"

💥Acharya Sushrut said that pain is the cardinal 
symptom of vitiated Vata Dosha. 
💥Pain does not arise in the absence of Vata and Dushit Rakta.
✅️Dry, imbalanced Vata Dosha leads to joint problems and achy bones.
💥Hadjod is a powerful herb that is suggested for bone health and bone fractures.

✅️Hadjod displays an intrinsically Katu (Pungent) and Madhura (Sweet) rasa (taste), 
which eventually becomes a Katu vipaka (pungent flavour after digestion or end taste). 
💥It equalizes and balances the Vata (air and ether) and Kapha (water and earth) doshas (energies or life forces), 
as well as effectively flushes out the AMA toxins (toxins that are present within the system and which often lead to incomplete digestion of food).
💥In addition, hadjod holds an inherent Ushna virya (Heating potency) and exhibits typical Laghu (Light), Ruksha (Dry) and Sara (Unstable) gunas (qualities or actions).
💥Hadjod is an effective herb that can heal fractured bones.
💥Hadjod can be used both internally and externally. 
✅️Hadjod is taken as juice with milk or ghee(on doctors advice for right dosage),tablets and powder form.

⚠️Hadjod has side effects when consumed in excess amounts like vomiting,dry mouth, headaches.
✅️Should not be consumed more than an inch.

❌️Hadjod must always be taken under a doctor's consultation.Do not try at home without doctor advice💥
✅️Personal Experience: It is very harsh in taste and has strong itching properties that you can feel as unbearable pain it goes down the throat.

💥Cooling & Nourishing Ayurvedic Superfruit!🤯

👉Known for its Sheeta (cooling), 
Kashaya (astringent), 
and Laghu (light) and oily  properties in Ayurveda, Falsa helps pacify Pitta and Vata doshas.

💥Benefits:
Daha- Reduces Burning Sensation. 
Hrudya- Heart Tonic,
Ruchiparda - improves taste.
Shopahara - relieving swelling & Anti-inflammatory.
Bruhmana- nourishing, improves weight.

💥Indicated in Tuberculosis, 
Supports digestion, reduces body heat, aids in bleeding disorders, skin issues & inflammation.

Falsa fruit causes constipation, so it can be consumed as Kashyam or Juice.
💥How to Make Falsa Juice:
Take 1/3 cup Falsa
Add 2–4 tbsp Mishri powder
Add 1/2 tsp black salt
Mash everything well and let it rest for 30 mins
Add 250 ml water, mix thoroughly
Sieve and serve.

💥Best Time to Consume: Mid-morning or early afternoon during summer.

💥Side Effects: Eating excessive raw Falsa may cause constipation. Best consumed as juice for easy digestion.

Disclaimer: For educational purposes only. Always consult a qualified Ayurvedic practitioner before trying any new remedy.

Ep-1 Language of Ayurveda 🌿✨
Dive into the ancient wisdom of Ayurveda by understanding its foundational terms:

Agni 🔥 – Your digestive fire, vital for transformation and metabolism.
It governs not just physical digestion but mental clarity and vitality.
A balanced Agni means strong immunity and radiant health.

Ama ☁️ – Toxic residue from poor digestion, the root of imbalance.
It clogs the body's channels and weakens energy flow.
Clearing Ama is the first step toward true healing.

Prana 🌬️ – Life force energy that sustains body and mind.
It flows through the breath and subtle energy channels.
When Prana is strong, you feel alive, clear, and connected.

Dosha ⚖️ – The three biological energies: Vata (air/ether), Pitta (fire/water), Kapha (earth/water).
Each person has a unique doshic makeup, or Prakriti.
Harmony among doshas means balance in body, mind, and emotions.

Soma 🌙 – The cooling, nourishing essence that promotes peace and rejuvenation.
It is linked to the moon’s energy and subtle bliss.
Cultivating Soma supports emotional calm, deep rest, and longevity.

Start your journey by understanding these guiding forces within you.

Mango seed 🤯The Forgotten Ayurvedic Gem🥭

While the juicy mango steals the spotlight, its seed — known as Aam Beej in Ayurveda — holds a powerhouse of medicinal value. Traditionally overlooked, this inner kernel has been used for centuries in Ayurvedic formulations for its potent healing properties.

✨ Key Ayurvedic Benefits of Mango Seed:

🔸 Balances Kapha & Pitta: Its astringent and cooling nature helps calm excess Pitta (heat) and Kapha (mucus, heaviness), making it useful in seasonal imbalances.

🔸 Supports Digestive Health:Mango seed powder aids in controlling loose stools and dysentery. It’s a trusted remedy for Grahani (IBS-like symptoms).

🔸 Promotes Oral Health: Used in powders or pastes, it strengthens gums, reduces inflammation, and combats bad breath.

🔸 Female Reproductive Support: Traditionally used to regulate menstruation and reduce excessive bleeding (Rakta pradara).

🔸 Cholesterol & Weight Management: It helps in breaking down fats and improving metabolism when used regularly under guidance.

How to make Homemade Mango seed Digestive Aid)- 

👉Collect 2-3 mango seeds from ripe mangoes,chop them into fine pieces or thin layers,sprinke some black salt on chopped mango seeds,mix well together and let it dry in shade for 2 days.
👉After drying it becomes crisp & chewy 
👉This can be consumed after heavy meals to aid digestion.

⚠️ Caution: Always use mango seed in powdered or processed form, not raw. Consult a qualified Ayurvedic practitioner before using it medicinally.
This video is only for informational purposes. 

🌱 Ayurveda teaches us: "Every part of nature has a purpose — we just need to look deeper." 🍃

This hair oil is slow-infused in sesame oil using the age-old puth pak method — soaking up sunlight and the potent goodness of these time-tested herbs:

🌱 Fenugreek (Methi) – Fights dandruff, strengthens roots & reduces hair fall

🍋 Amla – Rich in Vitamin C, boosts collagen, strengthens hair & adds shine
🌿 Bhringraj – Known as the “king of herbs” for hair growth and preventing hair loss

"Stop wasting this powerful Ayurvedic ingredient! 🌿 Here's why mango seeds deserve your attention. #AyurvedaLifestyle

In Ayurveda, mango seeds (known as Aam Beej or Aam ke Gutli) are valued for their medicinal and therapeutic properties. Although the fruit is more popular, the seed kernel is used in various traditional remedies. Here are some Ayurvedic uses of mango seeds:

🌿 1. Dental Health
👉Use: Powdered mango seed is used as a tooth powder.
👉Benefit: Helps prevent gum diseases, tooth decay, and bad breath due to its astringent and antibacterial properties.

🌿 2. Diarrhea and Dysentery

👉Use: Dried mango seed powder is taken with honey or buttermilk.
👉Benefit: Acts as an astringent and helps control loose motions and intestinal inflammation.

🌿 3. Weight Management

👉Use: Mango seed powder is consumed internally.
👉Benefit: It boosts metabolism and helps in managing fat absorption, thus aiding weight loss.

🌿 4. Cholesterol Control
👉Use: Powder or oil derived from mango seed.
👉Benefit: Contains healthy fatty acids that may help in reducing bad cholesterol (LDL).

🌿 5. Hair & Scalp Health
👉Use: Mango seed oil (also called mango butter) is applied to the scalp.
👉Benefit:Nourishes the scalp, prevents dandruff, and strengthens hair follicles.

🌿6. Skin Care
👉Use:  Mango seed butter is used in creams and balms.
👉Benefit: Rich in antioxidants, it moisturizes dry skin and soothes irritation.

 🌿7. Diabetes Management
👉Use: Mango seed powder consumed in controlled amounts.
👉Benefit: Said to help regulate blood sugar levels, though clinical evidence is limited.

Note: Always consult an Ayurvedic practitioner before starting any new herbal remedy, especially in case of chronic conditions or pregnancy.This video is only for informational purposes and doesn't substitute for medical diagnosis or treatment or advice.
